A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre sees it as a myth, stating that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, the Republican lawyers have reported that 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will affect negatively the rate of participation.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of American governments passed from 2009 to new laws making it more difficult for the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw it add 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced during the single year of 2011.
The new electoral law requires that voters have an identity card photo and proof of US citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce periods of polls, invalidate the right to register as Polling Day and withdraw citizens with a criminal record their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state requires voters to present an identity card photo.
Indiana was the first state to ask such a requirement.
The US Supreme Court upheld in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities moved rapidly to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present an identity card photo.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card of health insurance.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, or 21 million people to vote, do not possess photo identification cards issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID.
However, it often costs more than one hundred dollars to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions affect disproportionately young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters from 18 to 29 years do not have the ID card photo.
Much more.
The students, voters considered voting more for Democratic candidates, are not permitted in several states to use their ID card photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of the fishing or hunting clubs who vote more Republicans to use for voting cards issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
However, it appears that two Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
Moreover, Republican legislators have sponsored legislation abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the rights of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns have contributed to record approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 pushed the registration rate of 17% of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of polls.
For example, during the general election of 2008 in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, while they accounted for only 13% of voters in the state.
The same was true with Hispanics.
They represented only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In return, whites made up 76% of voters accounted for 46% of the electorate voting in advance.
Of course, the Democratic lawmakers and their supporters were strongly opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
Advocate General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of an identity card photo.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Critics Democrats denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed, and they see it as a clear aim to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A report by the Brennan Center for 2011 shows that states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes in the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential elections in 2012.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will affect negatively the rate of participation.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system.

