With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
Quite the opposite of the current monetary exchange, based on central banks, transactions identified and the costs of treatment between the stakeholders.
In addition, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, banking monopolies, led to the financial crisis.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure protocol for the exchange of BitTorrent, which enables the exchange of peer-to-peer files.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand Web sites accept bitcoins as gifts or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, has fallen to $2, five months later, before coming back today around a dozen dollars (prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts).
Nothing very impressive, compared to world trade in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She described bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success," "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency, such as "credits," used to move forward in a video game that you win by playing, or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and deals with trade.
With Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are custodians of the book of accounts, auditors, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network?
Each transaction between two users is actually between two Email addresses in the manner of an Email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A series of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a system of double encryption key.
The network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins traded exist in the book, distributed across the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner, sort of interim central banker, will have the privilege to add this extra line.
It is a phase of hash file, which is processing a large file into a shorter and unique digital fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number of "chop."
The aim is to find the number that gives a special footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once found, other knots check easily that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than 10 minutes), one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because both have different fingerprints.
The computer has solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this award is divided by two regularly, probably before the end 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to 100 millionth, leaving the room....
The difficulty of the challenge is also noted for each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Web sites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and stolen bitcoins deposits.
"The flaw is not related to the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a company to pay real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB is also the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But the cash is also lacking.
Weight actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
Others, such as the platform for blogs, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, have analyzed the book of accounts and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not found.
In November, "balances giants" have been launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of an instructional book on the currency, is a great believer in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or a mobile contactless payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, returning and cheaper.
The carrier manages its identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement among the merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They only need to provide an address, a phone can "photograph and recognize," said Pierre Noizat, who has thousands of users.
There is a general movement of hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin is needed, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, expects to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in the event of success of this currency.

