# genre=news sysid=limis-ncode-soul-primary origlang=fr docid=liberation/2012/12/01/160509
A constitution in force in Egypt
It is a new poker of President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which grants him full powers, he decided to play its protagonists.
Taking everyone short, he announced Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given two more months to this House to finish its work.
Nearly two years ago that Egypt is based on a draft text, several times amended which undermines institutional stability and led to legal entanglements.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, President perseveres in his "autocratic insanity," continuing "betraying its word" and "trampling on the law."
On the side of his supporters, it ensures that it is a way to end as soon as possible with the political and institutional crisis by speeding up the process of transition.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short time, forcing the Brotherhood to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, the Egyptians.
President, it is also a way to regain a popular and democratic legitimacy while the dispute rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for it, as he said in an interview with the US weekly Time.
Especially since this recourse to a hasty vote takes the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep full powers," these supposedly due to expire after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, Islamic majority, voted against the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing.
Mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing it had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done likewise.
In order to ensure that the necessary quorum, 11 people have been added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted.
Commentators have been amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the pendulum of the constituent was done improperly.
The text, which was still being voted last night, contains 234 articles.
Objects of all the attention, Article 2 finally remains identical to that of the 1971 constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafi parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to replace "principles" by "the rules," which would have allowed stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a sign of goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," are liberals, who see it as a communication.
Because according to them, the Islamisation of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which gives the Al-Azhar university an advisory role, particularly with regard to verify the compliance of laws with sharia law.
According to the expert in Egypt Sophie Pommier, it is worrisome because " people called to vote are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of a theocracy."
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next president of the university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no religious involvement.
With this constitution, it remains within the framework of the civilian government.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not scholars but academics, some trained in the French system " temper Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, because the words go to religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question could in future be the extent of the civilian judges are competent to decide on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is widely criticized because of the powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that they are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will be banned the trial of civilians in military courts, as requested by the associations of defence of human rights.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be fatal.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and the insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, the press in particular.
Moreover, no article echoes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef, Human Rights Watch.
The only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
The word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian President was scheduled to speak last night on television, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The support of the head of state will march on Saturday.

