Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as a 20th member of this agency, it is the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full fledged member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had engaged in close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed has been involved in a number of projects in the agency.
Poland's road to space, however, began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they were not always understanding.
I would like to mention the conference of A.?ternfeld at the observatory in Warsaw on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from her pioneering book "introduction to space travel."
The development of this young engineer (born in 1905) left viewers cold and years later?ternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski turned his attention to his work.
In 1934,?ternfeld won France's Robert marques and André Louis Hirsch for his book "introduction to space travel."
Dr Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) became a big propagateur of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagateur of the world-renowned astronaut, his contribution has been rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Since 1925 was built in Poland a hand car intended to be equipped with a rocket engine.
There is, unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or curb the hand car.
The only known information on the hand car are those of the press at the time.
Starting in 1933, the Polish artillery began to focus on the rockets.
The research was conducted by the institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
According to the documents that this research had reached the stage of the trial.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the searches were interrupted.
In 1937, plans for a hunting photoelectrically rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozi?ski, appeared in the press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna rakietobomba i lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were aimed at military use of the rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects using the technique of rockets were being carried out by the Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo - Naukowy"), who coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the start of the war ended.
After the war, other work on the aircraft were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish company Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a question of a company in the November 1954 issue of the journal, in which there are four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to space travel
At that time, artificial satellites had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research in the future.
At the beginning of the year 1956, the Polish company Astronautics (PTA) efforts to enter the International Astronautics Federation (created in 1951) and as early as autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice president of the International Astronautics Federation.
He kept his office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the ATP made a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1,800 metres had an 80 cm long and weighed slightly less than 5 kilograms.
Subsequently built an improved version, RM - 1A, and during summer 1959, flight tests of the two-stage rocket was launched in the desert of Bledov.
The rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kilograms.
The next prototype should have been able to make concrete scientific work - the rocket par-34 should have a range up to 14.5 kilometers and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was halted.
The Meteor rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, led to the first rocket.
The rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kilograms.
Three models (called Meteor 1A, 1B and 1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor rocket - 1A had an area with a volume of 0.4 per litre, whereas in Meteor 1B this volume was 0.34 per litre and Meteor 1C of 0.62 per litre.
The maximum range of all these types of gear was 37 kilometers.
In the period between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor missiles were developed in the aviation institute, the first flight trials started in October 1970.
The Meteor rocket had an initial weight of 380 kilograms and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kilograms at an altitude of about 60 kilometers.
Subsequently they built the Raytheon versions - 2H and Raytheon.
It is still necessary to mention the entry of Poland in the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national committee COSPAR two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland has also been involved in space exploration on Soviet space satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second Soviet cosmonaut program.

