The repeal of the law on utility work is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on public works.
This decision was raised in the public a lively discussion.
It is certainly interesting to examine this issue from a broader point of view.
The economic systems geared towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means that the various economic entities as well as the national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with a financial excessive speculation.
The significant differences in the price of labour (wages) generate tension on prices.
It should be put under this term the following meaning: a producer attempts by the importation of goods sold cheaply to withstand economic competition by making it more expensive " the price of a competitor, in order to remove a greater share of the market and to increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transfer production abroad, or buy at low prices, or disappear, the result is a high unemployment in the countries where prices are high compared to other economies.
Given that the private capital has no responsibility from the social point of view and thus responsibility for unemployment it creates, payroll taxes necessarily increase.
This intensifies the perfect unwillingness of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and to compensate for the social and economic damage to the whole of society by this race.
This situation is so well known that there is no need to provide concrete statistics.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital are resulting in different economies a situation in which the governments of different countries are forced to engage in a mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own people in order to attract foreign capital.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of the private capital without taking into account the social collapse.
This is evident mainly in the amendments of existing laws.
The aim is to compel economically its own people to accept the diktat of the price of private capital, particularly in the area of wages.
This happens through a system of economic constraints in the case of long-term unemployment and the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
The result is a growing poverty and deepening of differences between rich and poor.
In Germany, there has been for years public distribution of food for the poor who cannot meet their needs with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common that employees receive such salaries that the government is forced to pay extra to ensure that they reach the subsistence level.
Such a scandal, for example, has been updated in the case of employees working as assistants in the federal parliament.
The economy of virtually all Member States in the south of the EU are, without doubt, a similar situation in which, under pressure from a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), either to eke out a living with poverty wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day the private capital investment in their country.
Here we have to ask the question: where will this capital?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty from one country to another; this capital may not come, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to Latin America.
The liberal theory and the media say, that the state cannot make capital investment in its own economy, that the economy run led to an economic catastrophe.
The private capital in favour of the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
Then you have to wonder if the private capital does not influence, and even does not today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and the entire state.
The answer is undoubtedly yes.
The proof is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby and present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, by granting mutual benefits in the legislation, where everything is wrong, but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that because of the lack of financial resources, the national ministries delegate the preparation of draft laws to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills are adopted in the Bundestag.
The entire power does not come from the people, such as the Western-style constitutions, but powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that democracies oriented towards liberalism are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "the Crisis of the Roman Empire at the time of Julius Caesar and Pompey": "The state had long been deteriorating and functions were assigned by violence.
The blows of bribes, favors obtained illegally, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The kickbacks and corruption have increased without limits and people went to the elections with votes already sold... the honest people were unrelated to obtain functions, the result was once the state was 8 months without Consuls... "' really began to say that the solution to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man..." it is true that Appianos had in mind Pompey, but it was Caesar who has transformed irreversibly democracy in absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the current society is based on the preference of personal benefit, without regard for the interests of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and promote the interests of society as a whole.
As a result, now as in the past, a decline of elites, without any effort to carry out far-reaching reforms.
So we have to look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalisation of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of affairs, we can consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, social and humanitarian crises that we are now witnessing, as well as crimes against humanity as we know them by the old and recent history.
The repeal of the law on utility work is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and domestically, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
