The Argo film: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters composed of Islamic students stormed the US Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which backed his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer to the US administration of positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have severely undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was able to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, compounded later by the fiasco of the attempted release of the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate was in the United States, a wave of solidarity and a feeling anti-iranien.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The Argo film, the actor and directing Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory for America.
Just before it is occupied, six employees are out of encirclement of the embassy.
After complicated events, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get out of Iran through a daring coverage: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a team filming location for the filming of a blockbuster science fiction film.
Gender mix
The expert in slipping Tony Mendez required the cooperation of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines of this film, press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company had real offices.
Details of the operation remained long secret, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
The Affleck film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a political thriller designed realistically, but also a "we movie," the story of a successful coup, a betrayal - such as, for example, in the Ocean's trilogy eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The move: Tehran sequences documentary style (subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs from the time of the events and the way in which, thanks to these pictures, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no big differences).
Lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration.
And then scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has been able to restart his career in a remarkable manner.
Ridiculed actor, he became a respected stage director and his player has ceased to elicit wry remarks.
Argo is his third film after the dark cop "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also the first Affleck film that is not taking place in his home city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that put his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck is also proof of this sense of the atmosphere in Argo, where the role of Tehran "is bound" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film takes place in streets, during the reconstruction of actual facts; the initial sequence of the collapse of the embassy is impressive in its clarity that would suggest the confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, wrote a page of history.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the false shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many shares in too many places
The film and stage director has had to contend with a few exciting scenes in the film sense of the word.
He fared very well, he sometimes adds some elements to the reality and the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at the airport in Tehran is ruled out by a phone call in America and the prosecution on the airstrip are fairly drawn by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood members, their characters deserve a greater place and it is not far from here, only in this case.
The film Affleck lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he is a moderate interest, enjoying the achievement and the styles of the 1970s.
It leads to the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story yet, somehow, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services, such as omnipotent and omniscient, it is the case.

