WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning had been their source.
During the hearing Friday, Fein discussed with Manning forms that officers had met after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in the military prison in Quantico, where he was subjected to a maximum appendages from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers have asked questions to Manning and recorded his answers.
When Fein spoke about the forms, Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment of his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had been in the prison was generally "very professional."
The forms showed no complaints of abuse, although officers have directly questioned about his prison treatment, said Fein.
Manning said he had orally expressed concerns about some problems and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would, but they have not documented the problems.
"They have written" no problem " (after having addressed the concerns), and this does not mean that I did not raise any problems," said Manning.
The military judge, Col. Denise Lind, has also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special committee which met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months ago.
Manning said that his intention during the meeting was to amend its restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury."
The military said they had assigned this restrictive status -- a level under close surveillance for risk of suicide -- for its protection and safety of others.
"I wanted people to know that I was going well, and I wanted to withdraw this status... in order to enjoy a better quality of life, from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the base of the U.S. Marines at Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had contemplated suicide when he was in Kuwait and fainted again because of the heat.
He added that the fact of not having been kept abreast of what he was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very scary.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon in the cage," said Manning, on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only objects available were a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothing and his glasses.
He has tried to stay in motion, because sleep or stay open during the day was contrary to the regulations.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in the eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned the night, they woken up in order to be able to see his face.
Counsel for Manning filed a formal complaint for the treatment of Manning in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also Friday, the judge asked questions to Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- after being forced to sleep overnight in his cell at Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other prisoners one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time, he was allowed to be covered with a blanket during the appeal.
