Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night, because he would have tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his flip-flops to get hurt, but that he had not done so.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, his flip-flops, and his glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences during his detention and that it will greatly reduce his sentence if he were to be convicted by court martial, a trial should be held in early next year.
The defense said that Manning plans to plead guilty of less serious offences and to fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors who are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was detained in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, giving rise to the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defence.
