In a constantly connected world, it can be good to get bored.
I spent five hours at an airport during the Thanksgiving period, because our plane had mechanical problems and we had to wait for the arrival of another plane.
As a result, I have had enough time to reflect on the theme of boredom.
I am not going to lie.
Spend a day at an airport to wait for a flight is quite boring, even when you have books, magazines and to distract you (not to mention the duty-free shops).
But increasingly, some academics and experts in the child's development are praising boredom.
It is perfectly normal for us - and our children - bored from time to time, they say.
This would force the brain to borrow interesting paths, or even to feed creativity.
And as for the most part, we are constantly in front of several types of screens, we no longer know the benefits of boredom.
So should we embrace boredom?
Yes.
And not.
But I will come back to this.
First, like a lot of people, I thought that boredom was a fairly recent phenomenon, especially since we have more free time.
But this is not the case, "said Peter Toohey, a professor of Greco-Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of" Boredom: Lively History " (Yale University Press, 2011).
"The problem goes back very far," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii are graffiti depicting boredom, they date back to the first century.
Then there is the definition we give to boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined, and debated in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After going through numerous publications and submitted the idea to a discussion group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues have identified boredom as an experience that is "to want to do something, but not to engage in a satisfactory activity."
What distinguishes the boredom of apathy, he said, is that the person is not in the process of undertaking a task that she would like.
With apathy, he said, there is no desire to do something.
What is at the heart of the problem, he said, is "the interruption of the process of attention, coupled with a gloomy mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can strongly resemble a depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that if the two may be related, people who are bored tend to think that the problem is the environment or the world, while those who believe that the problem comes from them.
Sometimes, we sometimes think that we're bored when it is actually a matter of concentration.
As part of their study, "the Unengaged Mind: defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," which was published in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues have highlighted an earlier experiment in which participants listened to on tape, the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups have heard from the room beside her too much of a TV show who had no connection, others have just heard the TV, and the third group did not hear the soundtrack.
Those who have heard the TV at a low noise level said they were annoyed that the two other groups - they have had difficulty concentrating, but did not know why, and attributed the problem of concentration to boredom.
When you try to focus on a difficult task, an interruption of attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you make a boring task, "like watching objects on an assembly line, music can help you don't get bored."
In fact, he said, now we know that when you are wiggles or scrawls, these gestures, often seen as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay physically more alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to space to learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stay quiet," said Professor Fenske.
We all bored one day or another - the delay in my flight, a speaker with a voice lacking in sparkle, a particularly boring film.
But some people are more likely to be bored than others.
To measure this, researchers have developed a "scale of susceptibility to boredom" in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as, "one of the tasks that are performed, many of them are repetitive and monotonous," and "I have so many centres of interest that I don't have time to do everything."
Using such a scale, researchers have discovered that boys tend to be bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, and in particular need of many and varied stimuli.
But in general, adolescents are quickly blase.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor in individual and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment during which he contacted nearly 400 adolescents and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
He noted that 32% of teenagers reported being bored at school and during their duties at home, while 23% said they feel bored when they were not at school.
In contrast, 3% of parents reported being bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentages of today's boredom, or 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he added that he knew that "adolescence is a time when boredom reached its highest level," particularly because children and adolescents do not have much control over what they want to do.
If I based my question: boredom is it good for you?
Sometimes not, because in its extreme form, it can cause people to take physical risks absurd, make bets or abuse of certain substances to pass the time, as studies show.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers suggest a link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying the problem for more than two decades.
"Boredom is the way that the brain has found to tell you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU
But the brain does not always know what is the most appropriate thing to do.
If you are bored and you use this energy to play the guitar and cook, you will be happy.
But if you look at the TV, you will be happy in the short-term, but not in the long term.
So if your child is bored and you give it an iPad, it gets lonely, but he has not learned to deal with alone or autorégler, says Professor Fenske.
"This autorèglement move from a situation to another," he said.
Your child learns not only to entertain, he gets more control of himself in other areas.
I do not think that we should glorify boredom.
Just as I do not think we should criticise.
Feel comfortable outside the constant ferment that generate business and technology is the goal to which we should strive.
Professor Eastwood agrees on this point.
"We need to annoy us more often, but boredom evokes an acute and frenetic desire to be connected to something that has meaning," he said.
According to him, what people are looking for is a way to disconnect and appreciate the downtime.
"In an environment where we are constantly hyperstimulés," he added, "it is difficult to find ways to engage in something when the noise stops."

