The hardest job in the world: human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health by wearing 70 kilograms of sulphur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom the work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living in the Ijen Kawah volcano, in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gases emanating from the bowels of the earth hardens in contact with the air.
Having collected large rocks of sulphur, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilograms, he installed in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 metres of altitude, but the exhausted porters are more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a snail's pace, keeping the balance and not stumble and fall into the abyss.
