The Unasur summit ended without the Lima Declaration
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration has been made public, although it has been announced previously and theoretically adopted by the seven party representatives.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency said at the outset that it would be disclosed after the close of the summit, and said it would be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has consistently been limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential meeting with the message "private session, audio restricted" was published in the press room.
The little information circulating among the journalists were those given by the press of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document disclosed during the day was the list of presidents present, which has caused unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media calling for more important information.
Later, the presidency of Peru has sent an Email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not the official document that concluded the summit.
In October last year, Peru hosted the 3rd South American Summit - Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although it has been asked by the press body, it did not broadcast the statement called the Declaration of Lima, as had been previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, you can verify that the document was published in the month of March.
In the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they are limited to a maximum of obtaining information.
The summit was also concluded with the joint agreement between Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court in The Hague that a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the decision of the ICJ to hear the arguments of both parties in the trial that Lima filed against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and fulfil the verdict that will solve the disputes we have today before the international court," said President Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of the controversy, treaties and international tribunals," said President Piñera by shaking hands with President Humala, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they abide by the ICJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to abide by the decisions of the international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundary with Nicaragua it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was asked to open the deliberations in the morning and to close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The agent has read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the action lines of 31 projects had been established between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of the summit would "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits."
He was informed that action would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and against organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, access to the Internet at low prices in the whole of South America, and to assess jointly and effectively the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (Latin America) must not be complacent but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our peoples," concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 flagship projects that improve the connection of the areas of South America, especially in rural areas and border... by uniting our countries and generating new economic channels," said the Peruvian president in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were Peru and were on the cross-cutting areas of its territory, from the coast in Brazil, and that two were a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give more details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America remains a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and good relations with its neighbours, is another issue at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian president, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to review all these routes, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua, which will seek to have a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope to be able to say to President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," said the president Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City, where they planned to attend the power of the new president of this country, Enrique Pena Nieto.
Similarly, in the context of the summit, the Defence Ministers of the bloc will meet first to approve the Action Plan for the year 2013, which is trying to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the presidency pro tempore of the regional bloc.

